								bīnī, two by two,
								etc.

div.p:
The Numeral Adverbs answer the question quotiēns (
									quotiēs
								), how many times? how often?

The following adjectives are called Multiplicatives:—
simplex, single; duplex, double, twofold; triplex, triple, threefold;
quadruplex , quīnquiplex, septemplex, decemplex, centuplex, sēsquiplex (1 1/2), multiplex (manifold).

Temporals: bīmus , trīmus, of two or three years' age;
biennis , triennis, lasting two or three years;
bimēstris , trimēstris, of two or three months; bīduum, a period of two days; biennium, a period of two years.

Other derivatives are: ūniō,
									unity;
								bīniō, the two (of
								dice); 
									prīmānus

								of the first legion;
								prīmārius, of the first
									rank;
								dēnārius, a sum of
									10 asses
								bīnus (distributive),
									double, etc.

The adverb -cumque (-cunque) (cf. quisque ) added to the relative makes an indefinite relative, which is declined like the simple word: as, quīcumque , quaecumque , quodcumque, whoever, whatever;
cûiuscumque , etc.This suffix, with the same meaning, may be used with any relative: as, quāliscumque, of whatever sort; quandōcumque (also rarely
quandōque ), whenever; ubicumque, wherever.

